Victorianera, Stainer is known for his considerable influence as a composer of Anglican liturgical music, and his corpus of secular works - madrigals and songs - presents many surprises. He was a brilliant organist, a fine scholar, theorist, pedagogue and teacher - multifarious attributes which this study elucidates and understands as part of his wider musical personality. Stainer's life is a story of extraordinary social mobility. From lowly origins he rose to become organist of St Paul's Cathedral and Professor of Music at Oxford. Yet after his premature death in 1901 he suffered almost immediate neglect except for the popularity of a handful of works, among them I saw the Lord and The Crucifixion. In rehabilitating Stainer and the crucial contribution he made to musical life, this book examines the breadth of his work as a composer, and the important role he played in the regeneration of sacredand secular musical institutions in Victorian Britain. JEREMY DIBBLE is Professor of Music at Durham University. His previous books include studies of Parry and Stanford and he is the author of numerous articles on British music. He is currently working on a dictionary of hymnology.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aComposersvBiographyzEngland. 0aComposerszEnglandvBiography. 4aMusic. 7aMUSIC / History & Criticism.2bisacsh  aAnglican Liturgical Music.  aBritish Composer.  aChoral Music.  aJohn Stainer.  aMusic Scholar.  aOrganist.  aSacred Music.  aSecular Music.  aVictorian Era.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package pre 2013z978311143139040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781846155598?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781846155598423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781846155598/original  a978-3-11-143139-0  